cs|5|cp|6|fp|4|at|^-{ Introduction to Chapter 2 }
^-
|fp||cp||at|The original Learn To Play Bridge program focused mostly on declarer play and bidding. Defense, the third critical aspect of playing bridge, was largely ignored in that program due to considerations of size and comprehension.

Given that you already know how to play bridge and that you would like to improve your game, defense cannot be ignored any longer. About half of the material in this program, the sequel to Learn to Play Bridge, is about defense. By the time you have gone through the 3 chapters on defense that are contained in this program, you will be ready for just about anything that could arise at the bridge table!

Defense at bridge is a very important skill to master for one simple reason:

|
pg| ***** 1 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ You will end up as a defender on roughly half of the bridge deals that you ever play! }
^-
|
pg| ***** 2 ***** |


at|It's true. When the cards have been dealt, each of the 4 players are equally likely to become the declarer. You will be the declarer on approximately one quarter of the bridge deals that you will play. Your partner will also be the declarer about one quarter of the time. For the remaining half of the deals that come up in your career as a bridge player, you are going to be a defender.

Most people who learn to play bridge are bridge players for life. Hopefully you will be both alive and playing bridge for many years to come! If so, you are going to be defending a lot of bridge deals so you had better learn what defense at bridge is all about.

|
pg| ***** 3 ***** |


tb||

nt|^b@2^z@3
First a warning:

|
pg| ***** 4 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ The majority of bridge experts consider defense to be the most difficult part of the game. }
^-
This warning is not meant to scare you, but it is only fair that you know that some challenges lie ahead. If it will make you feel any better, there are plenty of experts who would argue that mastering bidding and/or declarer play is at least as difficult as learning how to defend well.

|
pg| ***** 5 ***** |


at|Now a promise:

|
pg| ***** 6 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{ Defense is hard, but it is worth the effort that it takes to learn to defend well. Working with 
 your partner on defense to defeat the declarer's contract is a very satisfying experience! }
^-
|
pg| ***** 7 ***** |


at|As you have already learned, figuring out which is the best card to play when you are the declarer can be a challenging exercise in logic. Deciding on the best card to play as a defender can also involve some complex problem solving, but while declarer play is largely an individual exercise, the partnership aspect of defense is extremely important.

|
pg| ***** 8 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ When you are the declarer, your partner (the dummy) just sits and admires your skills! }

|
pg| ***** 9 ***** |


cs|4|at|{ Defense is all about teamwork! For the defense to be effective, both members of the 
 partnership must learn to work together toward the same objective: defeat the contract! }
|
pg| ***** 10 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
Defense at bridge is fun because it encompasses the best parts of the other 2 main aspects of the game. A defender is faced with the same sort of technical challenges that the declarer is presented with, but being able to communicate effectively with your partner (a skill that is central to bidding) is also a cornerstone of sound defense.

Besides the partnership aspect of defense, there is another factor that makes this part of bridge very different (and often more difficult) than playing a hand as declarer:

|
pg| ***** 11 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ As the declarer, you know about all of the assets that your partnership has been 
 dealt (because you can see both your own hand and the cards in the dummy). }

|
pg| ***** 12 ***** |


cs|2|at|{ As a defender, this is not the case. You can see your own hand and you will be able  
 to see the dummy after the opening lead, but you cannot see your partner's cards! }
^-
|
pg| ***** 13 ***** |


at|The fact that the declarer can see all of the partnership's cards is important. For example, in a notrump contract, the declarer will know which suits represent the best chances for winning tricks. If there is a trump suit, the declarer has all the information he needs to know regarding whether or not he should try for a ruff in either the dummy or in his own hand.|va|8|at|
The same is not true on defense. Since a defender cannot see his partner's hand, he will often have no idea which of his partner's suits contain length or strength (that is, which suits can be used to develop defensive tricks at notrump). Similarly, a defender will often have to guess whether or not he should try for a ruff (or try to give his partner a ruff). It is hard to give your partner a ruff on defense unless you know that he is both void in a given suit and not void in trump!

|
pg| ***** 14 ***** |


qx|nt,Opening leads against notrump contracts|


nt|^b@2^z@3|
cs|5|cp|6|fp|4|
at|
^-{ Opening leads against notrump contracts }
^-
|fp||cp||at|As you just learned, many bridge experts consider defense to be the most difficult part of the game of bridge. One of the main reasons why defense can be difficult is that, unlike the declarer, the defenders cannot see their partners' hands. Not knowing the partnership's combined assets (in terms of long suits and high cards) often makes it hard to know which suit(s) represent potential sources of tricks for the defense.

Once the opening lead has been made, both defenders are able to look at the dummy. On many deals, the sight of the dummy will offer clues as to the best course of action on defense.

|
pg| ***** 15 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ The opening leader has the unique problem of having to select a card to play without 
 even being able to see the dummy. The opening leader often feels as if he is in the dark! }
^-
For this reason, the process of selecting the best opening lead on a given hand is far from easy. Still, this is a logical place to begin the study of defense at bridge. After all, every bridge deal contains an opening lead (except for passouts of course) and you will find that you will be the opening leader on roughly one quarter of the bridge deals that you play.

The opening lead is the first chance the defense has to strike a blow against the declarer and on many deals the opening lead will force the defenders down a particular path. An effective opening lead will often make the difference between the success and the failure of a contract. 

|
pg| ***** 16 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ Make no mistake about this: opening leads are ^*Ivery^*N important! }

|
pg| ***** 17 ***** |


tb||

nt|^b@2^z@3
In this program, the study of opening leads has been broken down into 2 topics: opening leads against notrump contracts and opening leads against trump contracts. Selecting the best opening lead when there is no trump suit is usually easier (since ruffs need not be considered) so we will start our discussion there.

While the defenders and the declarer have completely opposite objectives (the declarer tries to win enough tricks to make the contract while the defenders try to prevent this from happening), many of the techniques that you are familiar with from your studies of declarer play can also be applied to defense.

|
pg| ***** 18 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ In particular, you have learned that the declarer in a notrump contract should 
 often try to establish winners in long suits in his own hand and/or in the dummy. }

|
pg| ***** 19 ***** |


cs|1|at|{ The same principle applies when defending against a notrump contract. 
 The defenders should try to establish winners in their long suits. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 20 ***** |


at|In a sense, this is easier said than done. Since the opening leader cannot even see the dummy (let alone his partner's hand), he will often have a difficult time knowing which suit represents the defenders' best chance for establishing winners. Still, the opening leader has to do the best that he can. On many deals the opening lead amounts to little more than a guess, but the following piece of advice will take you a long way toward making good opening leads against notrump contracts:

|
pg| ***** 21 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ Against a notrump contract it is often best to lead from your longest and strongest suit. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 22 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|cs|3|at|
Consider the following hand as an example:

|ht|c|va|5|at|^D{|ih|pst98765h32ckq2da2|at|}|ht|c|va|5|cs|1|at|^M{|ia|   1np3nppp|at|}

South, the dealer, opened the bidding with 1NT and was raised to 3NT by North. Imagine that you are sitting West and that you hold the hand shown above. You have to select an opening lead. What suit would you lead from?

|
pg| ***** 23 ***** |


hs|sd|at|Let's consider each of the 4 suits. The diamond suit contains your one and only Ace. The nice thing about leading an Ace against a notrump contract is that you will certainly win the trick as there is no way that the declarer will be able to ruff!

Experience has shown, however, that the opening lead of an Ace against a notrump contract is rarely a good start for the defense. There are 3 good reasons for this:

|cs|4|at|^-{ 1) Aces rarely "go away". Save your Ace for later. You will still win a trick with it. }

|
pg| ***** 24 ***** |


cs|2|at|{ 2) The @DA might be a useful entry for regaining the lead later in the play. }

|
pg| ***** 25 ***** |


cs|1|at|{ 3) It would be nice if the declarer had to use a high diamond (like the @DK) to force your @DA! }
|
pg| ***** 26 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|ls|sd|hs|sc|cs|3|at|
How about leading a club?

|ht|c|va|5|at|^D{|ih|pst98765h32ckq2da2|at|}|ht|c|va|5|cs|1|at|^M{|ia|   1np3nppp|at|}

You have both the @CK and the @CQ. If your partner has the @CA then the defense can win at least 3 tricks in the club suit. It is more likely that either the declarer or the dummy has the @CA (because their bidding suggests that they hold most of the outstanding high cards), but leading a high club might still work out well.

Suppose that declarer was dealt the @CA and that you select either the @CK (or the @CQ) as your opening lead. If declarer ducks his @CA you will have won a trick and if declarer wins the @CA you will have established a winner in clubs. You will almost certainly be able to win a future trick with the @DA and cash the club trick that your clever lead set up.

On the surface this seems like a good plan, but...

|
pg| ***** 27 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ You do not have a long club suit and the bidding gives you no reason to believe that your 
 partner has a long club suit either. Remember, leading long suits at notrump is the way to go!}
|
pg| ***** 28 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|ls|sc|hs|sh|cs|3|at|
Hearts anyone?

|ht|c|va|5|at|^D{|ih|pst98765h32ckq2da2|at|}|ht|c|va|5|cs|1|at|^M{|ia|   1np3nppp|at|}

By now you should understand that a heart would make an unattractive opening lead from this hand. Hearts is your shortest and weakest suit and leading a heart is completely contrary to the principle of selecting an opening lead from your longest and strongest suit.

|
pg| ***** 29 ***** |


ls|sh|hs|ss|at|The only suit left to consider is the spade suit and, as you have probably guessed, the opening lead of a spade represents your best chance to defeat the contract. It is not a coincidence that spades happens to be your longest suit.

That doesn't mean that you necessarily will defeat the contract after selecting a spade as an opening lead. It is not at all unlikely that 3NT will succeed regardless of what you lead. In addition, it is entirely possible that any of the other 3 suits could turn out to be a more effective opening lead than a spade. 

|
pg| ***** 30 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ Choosing an opening lead is not an exact science. 
Opening leads do not come with any guarantees! }
^-
|
pg| ***** 31 ***** |


