cs|3|at|^-{ Good defenders use the cards that they play for more than just winning tricks. 
Some cards can be signals used to tell your partner more about your hand. }|
pg| ***** 36 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|ht|c|cs|2|at|^-{ Remember, just as you cannot see your partner's hand when you are defending, he 
 cannot see your hand either. The cards that you play can help partner to visualize your hand. }
|
pg| ***** 37 ***** |


ht|q|cs|1|at|{ If your partnership makes agreements about which cards will always be led from certain 
 holdings (and if you follow these agreements) defense becomes a whole lot easier! }
^-
|
pg| ***** 38 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3Hopefully this important principle makes some sense to you. If not, don't worry as we will be exploring the concept of signaling on defense in much greater detail before too long.

Even if you fully understand the concept of signaling, it is not clear why the @S10 is the proper spade to lead. What makes the @S10 a better signal than any of West's other spades?|
pg| ***** 39 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|cs|1|ht|c|at|^-{ The main reason why the @S10 is the proper spade to lead is that most bridge players always
 lead the 10 from a suit headed by the 1098. The @S10 is what is known as a standard lead. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 40 ***** |


at|There are tables of standard leads from various holdings. If you and your partner are both familiar with the standard leads, you will be able to draw inferences from each others' leads. |
pg| ***** 41 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3Later in this chapter the table of standard leads will be presented (don't worry - it is not difficult to memorize). The main purpose of the current lesson, however, is to learn which suit to lead against a notrump contract, not which card to lead from that suit.

Let's see how a spade opening lead might work out in practice.

|
pg| ***** 42 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|lc|st|pc|st|hs|nd|hs|wd|at|Suppose you lead the @S10. The sight of all of the diamonds in the dummy makes it clear that the @DA would not have been a very good opening lead on this deal. It is true that you would have won the first trick if you had led the @DA, but you would have set up 5 diamond tricks for the declarer in the process. You will see very soon that saving the @DA to win a later trick was a very good idea!

|
