The first lesson that we learned about opening leads against notrump was that leading the longest suit that you were dealt will usually be a good start for the defense.  Every bridge hand contains at least 1 suit with at least 4 cards. As such, most of your opening leads against notrump contracts will be from suits with at least 4 cards in them. Furhermore, because we like to lead from strong suits, most of our opening leads against notrump will be from suits that are headed by at least one honor card.

We have seen situations, however, when it is best to lead a short and/or weak suit against notrump. Sometimes the opponents will have bid your longest suit and sometimes your partner will have made a bid (or double) that will cause you to lead a short and/or weak suit.

We will now examine the standard opening leads against notrump from suits that are short (that is, less than 4 cards long) and/or weak (that is, suits with no honor cards):

